f.d:
Letters are both āli and kāli:
Āli exhibitors, ཨི etcetera, are four;
Kāli are thirty.

Ten of them are suffixes and
Five of those are also prefixed;
The not-placed ones number twenty.

Of the ten suffix letters,
The tenth positioned at the end of some name
And the second āli connected to it;
The eighth positioned at the end of some name;
And that also having the second, ཨུ, connected to it;
The third positioned at the end of some name
And the second āli connected to it;
The fourth and ninth in fact; and another yet,
Are the Object, Purpose, Support,
Identity, and Timing la-terms.

For the first two, the first is harmonious then
For the third, fifth, and tenth, a ཀྱ་ connection;
For the seventh itself, the seventh;
And for the remainder a གྱ་ connection is so.

Extremely female is affixed to neutral,
Female, and extremely female itself.
What is not affixed is like this:
Male is not affixed to neutral;
Female also does not get affixed to male;
Neutral is not affixed itself to itself.

If you ask, “Why is the affixing done?”
Male because of making past and other;
Neutral both and on account of the present;
Female because of self and present and future;
Extremely female because of them equally.

The ten suffix letters are divided into three:
Male, female, and neutral.
Male is held to be three beings strongest, middling, weakest;
Female to be female and extremely female;
Neutral to be three: changeable,
Dual-character, and characterless.

The prior one is connected exactly to the five prefixes.
The way of drawing the subsequent one:
Male will draw a male name ending;
Female will draw a female name ending;
And neutral a neutral one.

སུ་རུ་ར་དུ་ན་ལ་ and ཏུ་ are the seven la-equivalents;
They are used for cases two, four, and seven,
And with identity and timing.

ས་ gets སུ་; ག་བ་ and forceful ད་ get ཏུ་;
ང་ད་ན་མ་ར་ and ལ་ get དུ་;
And འ་ and no ending get ར་ and རུ་.

Their mode of connection is: ན་མ་ར་ and ལ་ get གྱི་;
ད་བ་ and ས་ get ཀྱི་; ག་ and ང་ get གི་; and
འ་ and no ending get འི་ and ཡི་.

ནས་ and ལས་ source, segregate, and include.
For actual source, either one may be connected;
Concordant-class segregation gets ནས་ and non-concordant ལས་;
For inclusion only the term ནས་ is used.

ཅི་ཇི་སུ་ and གང་ are terms of generality:
ཅི་ with ཞིག་སྟེ་སླད་འདྲ་ and ཕྱིར་;
ཇི་ with སྙེད་སྲིད་ལྟར་བཞིན་ and སྐད་;
སུ་ to persons; and གང་ to all.

As for the phrase linkers ཞིང་ and so on:
ང་ན་མ་འ་ར་ལ་ endings and no ending get ཞིང་ཞེས་ཞེ་འོ་ཞེ་ན་ཞིག་;
ག་ད་བ་ and forceful ད་ endings get ཅིང་ཅེས་ཅེ་འོ་ཅེ་ན་ཅིག་;
ས་ endings, except for special ཞེས་, get ཤིང་ཤིག་ཤེ་འོ་ཤེ་ན་.

In prose where there is much meaning, at the boundary of a name;
To divide medium meanings; at completed lesser meanings;
And in verse at an ending ག་, a single shad should be made.

They are used to give five meanings:
case two, “site of a function” as in ཤར་ཕྱོགས་སུ་འགྲོ། “going to the east”;
case four, “necessity and purpose” as in རྟར་རྩྭ་བྱིན། “gave grass to the horse”;
case seven, “site of support” as in ལྷ་ཁང་དུ་རྟེན་གསུམ་ཡོད། “there are three representations in the shrine-room”;
the internal division of case two called “identity” as in འོད་དུ་ འཚེར། “radiating light”;
and the internal division of case seven called “timing” as in ཉི་མའི་འཆར་ཁ་རུ་འགྲོ། “go at sun-rise”.
Their mode of connection is as follows.

“Letters are both āli and kāli:
Āli exhibitors, ཨི etcetera, are four;
Kāli are thirty.”

“Ten of them are suffixes and
Five of those are also prefixed;
The not-placed ones number twenty.”

“Of the ten suffix letters,
The tenth positioned at the end of some name
And the second āli connected to it;
The eighth positioned at the end of some name;
And that also having the second, ཨུ, connected to it;
The third positioned at the end of some name
And the second āli connected to it;
The fourth and ninth in fact; and another yet,
Are the Object, Purpose, Support,
Identity, and Timing la-terms.”

“For the first two, the first is harmonious then
For the third, fifth, and tenth a ཀྱ་ connection;
For the seventh itself, the seventh;
And for the remainder a གྱ་ connection is so.
Those, with ཨི་ connected, are the site of the connective.”

The persons, the beginners, wanting to put effort into the training associated with some field of learning, must at the very outset learn to read and pronounce each component letter in accordance with the production places, producers, and inner and outer efforts shown in the texts on letters and then each of those coupled with the enunciation of each tone of the vowels.

Then, their training for the purpose of knowing how to read well will be to learn how the threefold five prefixes, thirty name-bases which are the fronting’s recipients, and ten suffixes are combined together into one intertsheg but in a way that would be easy for a child to follow.

Having learned how to read, the persons have to engage the suffixes—and the prefixes included in them, too—as they are explained in the Application of Gender Signs:
“Which term it is to be placed on;
Which letter is to be placed;
How it is to be placed;
Why it needs to be placed.”

Those are the four types of connection and they connect the persons with: listening to the guru’s good explanations; con- templating the meanings of those good explanations correctly for their own sakes; and having mastered them, teaching them to others for their sake. This sort of connection is the training for becoming learned.

The explanation of The Application of Gender Signs has three parts:

1. Explanation of the divisions of the general gender of the name-base letters;
2. Explanation of the application of the gender of prefix letters;
3. Explanation of the application of the gender of suffix letters.

“Each of those also has four do’s:
To which does it affix; which does it;
How does it affix; and why is it done?”

“What is not affixed is like this:
Male is not affixed to neutral;
Female also does not get affixed to male;
Neutral is not affixed itself to itself.
If it is in contact with its own section:
It is not affixed to either male or female;
Neutral and female are also like that.”

“Male because of making past and other;
Neutral both and on account of the present;
Female because of self and present and future;
Extremely female because of them equally.”

“Male is held to be three beings strongest, middling, weakest;
Female to be female and extremely female;
Neutral to be three: changeable,
Dual-character, and characterless.”

“Further, it is done with four do’s:
To which does it affix; which does it;
How does it affix; and why is it done?”

“Meaning has two aspects:
The way that the prior one changed;
The way that the subsequent one will change.”

“Male will draw a male name ending;
Female will draw a female name ending;
And neutral a neutral one.”

“If that happened, the world would be totally
Without expressions conveying meaning;
The propounders of the Vedas would not exist;
And the shrāvaka-, pratyeka-, and buddha-
Trainings also would become non-existent.”

The lake-born lotuses, the guiding experts, have mostly closed,
And people just make up things, to make themselves feel good;
How to dispel the primordial darkness of beings of the cold land?

The lines of tulkus mostly are sidetracked into activities of the senses;
Meditators mostly are lost in the fraud of goods;
Learned people mostly are engaged in the trading and working!
Oh my! Who will uphold the teachings of the sage?

The ears of the intention that seeks what is meaningful are deeply blocked;
The eyes of the view seeing good and bad are blinkered with obscuration,
The negative forces of bias puff up the mind with pride;
The flicker of their “good explanations” will do what?

How do they affix?
Male affixes to a stronger sound effort;
Neutral affixes to a moderate one;
Female in a weaker way, and
Extremely female in flat one.

ka in the three cases of being bare, super-fixed, and
sub-fixed e.g., བཀའ། བསྐ། བཀྱེ། བཀྲ། བསྐྱངས།;
ca only as a fronting to the bare letter e.g., བཅས། བཅོམ། བཅུག;

ta in the two cases of being bare and super-fixed e.g., བཏབ། བཏུད། བཏག ། བརྟག ། བལྕ། བསྟར།;
tsa bare and superfixed as in བཙས། བཙོས། བཙུགས། བརྩེགས།;
ga in the three cases of being bare, super-fixed and sub-fixed as in བགོ། བགྲང་། བགྱིས། བརྒལ། བསྒོམས།;
nga only as a fronting to the super-fixed letter as in བརྔམས། བསྔགས།;
ja only as a fronting to the super-fixed letter as in བརྗེས། བརྗིད།;
nya only as a fronting to the super-fixed letter as in བརྙན། བསྙེན།;
da in the two cases of being bare and super-fixed as in བདེ། བརྡ། བལྡག བསྡད།;
na only as a fronting to the super-fixed letter as in བརྣག བསྣམས།;
dza only as a fronting to the super-fixed letter as in བརྫེས། བརྫིས།;
zha only as a fronting to the bare letter as in བཞག བཞི། བཞེས།;
za in two cases of bare and sub-fixed e.g., བཟང་། བཟི། བཟུང་། བཟེད། བཟོ། བཟླས།;
ra only as a fronting to the sub-fixed letter as in བརླབས།;
sha only as a prefix to the bare letter as in བཤད། བཤེས།; and
sa in the two cases of being bare and sub-fixed as in བསམ། བསུ། བསེ། བསོས། བསྲིས། བསྲུངས། བསྲེས། བསྲོས།.

The female ’a letter is affixed to the ten letters ga, ja, da, ba, dza, kha, cha, tha, pha, and tsha of which it is affixed to:

ga both bare and sub-fixed འགའ། འགྲོ། འགྱེལ།;
ja fronted to the bare letter འཇལ།;
da both bare and sub-fixed འདབ། འདི། འདྲ།;
ba bare and sub-fixed e.g., འབའ། འབྲོག འབྱོར།;
dza fronted to the bare letter འཛེར། འཛུམ། འཛོལ།;
kha bare and sub-fixed འཁོར། འཁྲུལ། འཁྲི། འཁྱིར།;
cha fronted to the bare letter འཆད། འཆང་། འཆར།;
tha fronted to the bare letter འཐོབ།;
pha bare and sub-fixed འཕར། འཕྲེང་། འཕྱི།; and
tsha fronted to the bare letter as in འཚལ།.

“How do they affix?
Male affixes to a stronger sound effort;
Neutral affixes to a moderate one;
Female in a weaker way, and
Extremely female in flat one.”

“Letters are both āli and kāli:
Āli, explicators ཨི etcetera, are four;
Kāli are thirty.”
